What is ggplot?

  1. Name the aesthetics, geoms, scales, and facets of the above visualisation. Also name any statistical transformations or special coordinate systems.

Specifications of the Cool density and scatter plot of baseball data plot:

  • Aesthetics: none defined by the user, the plot uses the default
  • Geoms: the points geoms is used, meaning the data is displayed in a scatter plot, as well as the 2d density, which displays the data according to density curves
  • Scales: the scales are defined automatically
  • Facets: there are no facets, the whole data is displayed in one place
  • Other: the labels for the axis and the title are changed, as well as the theme, which is set to minimal

Visual exploratory data analysis

Histogram

  1. Use geom_histogram() to create a histogram of the grades of the students in the gg_students dataset. Play around with the binwidth argument of the geom_histogram() function.
histogram <-
  ggplot(gg_students, aes(x = student_grade)) +
  geom_histogram()
histogram
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

histogram <-
  ggplot(gg_students, aes(x = student_grade)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 1)
histogram

histogram <-
  ggplot(gg_students, aes(x = student_grade)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.5, boundary = 0)
histogram

Density

  1. Use geom_density() to create a density plot of the grades of the students in the gg_students dataset. Add the argument fill = "light seagreen" to geom_density().
density <-
  ggplot(gg_students, aes(student_grade)) +
  geom_density(fill = "light seagreen")
density

  1. Add rug marks to the density plot through geom_rug(). You can edit the colour and size of the rug marks using those arguments within the geom_rug() function.
density <- 
  density +
  geom_rug(color = "Coral", size = 1)
density

  1. Increase the data to ink ratio by removing the y axis label, setting the theme to theme_minimal(), and removing the border of the density polygon. Also set the limits of the x-axis to go from 0 to 10 using the xlim() function, because those are the plausible values for a student grade.

Here, we have to redefine density as geoms overlay, so we would never be able to take out the border of the density polygon.

density <-
  ggplot(gg_students, aes(student_grade)) +
  geom_density(fill = "light seagreen", color = NA) +
  geom_rug(color = "Coral", size = 1) +
  ylab(element_blank()) +
  theme_minimal() +
  xlim(0, 10)
density

Boxplot

  1. Create a boxplot of student grades per programme in the gg_students dataset you made earlier: map the programme variable to the x position and the grade to the y position. For extra visual aid, you can additionally map the programme variable to the fill aesthetic.
bxplt <- 
  ggplot(gg_students, aes(x = programme, y = student_grade, fill = programme)) +
  geom_boxplot()
bxplt

  1. What do each of the horizontal lines in the boxplot mean? What do the vertical lines (whiskers) mean?

The lower and upper horizontal lines (hinges) correspond to the first and third quartiles and the central one corresponds to the median. The vertical lines (whiskers) go from the minimum to the maximum values (excluding outliers, which are shown as points).

Two densities

12 Comparison of distributions across categories can also be done by adding a fill aesthetic to the density plot you made earlier. Try this out. To take care of the overlap, you might want to add some transparency in the geom_density() function using the alpha argument.

density <-
  ggplot(gg_students, aes(student_grade, fill = programme)) +
  geom_density(color = NA, alpha = 0.5) +
  geom_rug() +
  ylab(element_blank()) +
  theme_minimal() +
  xlim(0, 10)

Line plot

  1. Use geom_line() to make a line plot out of the first 200 observations of the variable Volume (the number of trades made on each day) of the Smarket dataset. You will need to create a Day variable using mutate() to map to the x-position. This variable can simply be the integers from 1 to 200. Remember, you can select the first 200 rows using Smarket[1:200, ].
nSmarket <- 
  Smarket %>% 
  mutate(Day = c(1:1250))
ln <- 
  ggplot(nSmarket[1:200, ], aes(x = Day, y = Volume)) +
  geom_line()
ln

  1. Give the line a nice colour and increase its size. Also add points of the same colour on top.
ln <- 
  ggplot(nSmarket[1:200, ], aes(x = Day, y = Volume)) +
  geom_line(colour = "Antique White 4", size = 1) + 
  geom_point(colour = "Antique White 4")
ln

  1. Use the function which.max() to find out which of the first 200 days has the highest trade volume and use the function max() to find out how large this volume was
day <- which.max(nSmarket[1:200, ]$Volume)
volume <- max(nSmarket[1:200, ]$Volume)
  1. Use geom_label(aes(x = your_x, y = your_y, label = "Peak volume")) to add a label to this day. You can use either the values or call the functions. Place the label near the peak!
ln <-
  ln +
  geom_label(aes(x = day, y = volume, label = "Peak volume"))
ln

Faceting

  1. Create a data frame called baseball based on the Hitters dataset. In this data frame, create a factor variable which splits players salary range into 3 categories. Tip: use the filter() function to remove the missing values, and then use the cut() function and assign nice labels to the categories. In addition, create a variable which indicates the proportion of career hits that was a home run.
baseball <-
  Hitters %>%
  filter(!is.na(Hitters$Salary))

baseball <-
  baseball %>% 
  mutate(SalaryTiers = cut(baseball$Salary, breaks=c(0, 425, 750, 2460), labels = c("Rich", "Very Rich", "Extremely Rich"))) %>% 
  mutate(HmRunProportion = (baseball$HmRun / baseball$Hits))

  1. Create a scatter plot where you map CWalks to the x position and the proportion you calculated in the previous exercise to the y position. Fix the y axis limits to (0, 0.4) and the x axis to (0, 1600) using ylim() and xlim(). Add nice x and y axis titles using the labs() function. Save the plot as the variable baseball_plot.
baseball_plot <-
  baseball %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = CWalks, y = HmRunProportion)) +
  geom_point() +
  ylim(0, 0.4) + 
  xlim(0, 1600) +
  labs(x = "CWalks", y = "Home Runs Proportion")
baseball_plot

  1. Split up this plot into three parts based on the salary range variable you calculated. Use the facet_wrap() function for this; look at the examples in the help file for tips.
baseball_plot <-
  baseball_plot +
  facet_wrap(baseball$SalaryTiers)
baseball_plot

Final Exercise

  1. Create an interesting data visualisation based on the Carseats data from the ISLR package.
library(ISLR)

Is the Advertising related to the Price? Or is it more related to the Population?

adv <-
  Carseats %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = Advertising, y = Price, color = Population)) +
  geom_point()
adv

It does seem that the ones with most Advertising are in places with higher Population, and are sold for a higher Price. However, the rest of the plot is not very interesting.

Let us compare the Companys Prices with the Competitors Prices:

prices <-
  Carseats %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = CompPrice, y = Price)) +
  geom_point()
prices

It does seem that there is a loosely linear relation between the two.

Lastly, something that might be interesting to look at is how the Education level affects how much the company uses Advertising in a certain location. We would expect that the higher the Education, the lower the Advertising, so we are expecting an inversely proportional relation.

edu_adv <- 
  Carseats %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Advertising, y = Education)) +
  geom_point()
edu_adv

The data seems to have almost no correlation, unlike what we expected, so the Carseat company should maybe think about changing their strategy
